<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-653-896  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 653 896.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  May 30 1990 n1510 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CoCom poised to throw open Eastern gateway. (CoordinatingCommittee set to drop trade restrictions)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gregg, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Cocom, the Coordinating Committee for Multilateral ExportControls, charged with controlling high-technology exports to theEastern Bloc countries, will be seeking to reduce the scope of itsresponsibilities when it meets in Paris in early June.andP;  Plans areto eliminate embargoes in some 30 of the currently 120 categories,and to further relax restrictions in some 13 of the remaining 90.andO;Among those categories to be eliminated are discrete transistors,thyristors, and instruments in the widest sense, while furtherrelaxation is expected in the areas of test and automated testequipment (ATE).andP;  While American representatives to the conferencewill be most concerned with ensuring that no technology that couldbe turned to military use slips through, others are more concernedthat the transfer of technology may mean increased competition ata later date.andP;  One area in which the Eastern Europeans do not lagfar behind their Western European colleagues is semiconductorproduction, although both Eastern and Western Europeansemiconductor production lags both the US and the Japanese.andO;Telecommunications is one area in which the Eastern Europeans areparticularly hungry for technology and product.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EuropeInternational TradeExportCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsEmbargo.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   Eastern Europe GDP per capita estimates. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>